    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-05-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-05-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="287" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d287">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Uhl</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Breckinridge</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-05-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 16,
                                1895</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 57.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I inclose a copy of a dispatch from our
                            minister at Peking,<note n="1" xml:id="d287fn1">See ante, <ref target="frus1895p1#pg_195">p. 195</ref>.</note> stating that the
                            Russian minister at that capital had, under the regulations of his
                            Government, declined to issue a passport or some official paper to
                            certain American missionaries residing at Kalgan, in China, enabling
                            them to take temporary refuge in Russian territory, in case the outbreak
                            of an insurrection in China imperiled their lives.</p>
                <p>You may take occasion to inquire whether the Russian regulations against
                            the residence or travel of foreign ecclesiastics or missionaries in
                            Siberia are as strict as Count Cassini interprets them to be, even to
                            the inhospitable degree of denying shelter to citizens of a friendly
                            State whose lives might be imperiled.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edwin F. Uhl</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
